metadata.name: Turbulence #415
metadata.description:
Swirly shapes are rendered by passes of poisson samples of a warped noise field. The noise shifts with each pass, creating a layered effect. 

Dense editions may take over 2 minutes to draw fully.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume at any time during the drawing.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a not 1:1 variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

Common:
- 43 set palettes plus many more with combinations
- 3 color distribution methods
- 50/50 dark
- 50/50 monochrome with bright highlights 
- 3 drawing styles: lines, points, colored pencils
- 5 noises effects: full screen, distance from center, distance from bottom, horizontal center, vertical center, random circles, 3,5, or 7 horizontal and vertical bars
- Poisson point distribution based on set layers or the noise value

Rare
- 15% chance of a dark monochrome with gold strands

metadata.name: Action Fields #339
metadata.description:
A generative painting based on abstract expressionism and the action paintings of Jackson Pollock.

Several different flow fields are used to create paths which are then painted in one of four different styles (pastel, paint, Pollock, black+gold). Additional features affect the background, path length + angles, level of detail, and mess (drips and splats). 

NOTES: 
- Some variations of the Pollock style may appear slightly different between browsers, but will render consistently in the same browser. 
- On slower devices, it may take some time to being drawing due to the background rendering.
- If you get a browser warning that the page is taking a long time, press continue.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1200x928px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 5,000 px. The ideal higher resolution is 2,000px.

metadata.name: The Esoteric Form #23
metadata.description:
The circle is an amazing strange geometrical form, it is by far the simplest geometric shape that exists, you might disagree with that, but actually, there are hundreds of pages long of mathematical proof of why it is, it's called "The Poincaré conjecture" this is one of the most difficult problems that stayed unsolved 20th century to prove that a circle is the simplest shape until it was demonstrated in 2003. When you see a drawing circle, it's a circle in two dimensions, right? What would it look like if it was in three dimensions, it's a sphere; same shape but more dimensions, but it's still the simplest kind of shape that exists in three dimensions. No matter how many dimensions you add, according to the Poincaré conjecture, it will always be the simplest shape. Even though it seems straightforward, there are extremely profound difficult problems within it.

The astonishing thing about circles is what we can do with them, particularly by using the majestic number π and connecting straight and curved lines using topological or geometrical functions. "The esoteric form" project is an example of how a circle can take on countless shapes and unusual, vibrant forms while also being simple and complex at the same time.

Press [s] to save captured image to png (2200px x 2200px)
Wait a moment it takes a while to be rendered (Up to 30s)
---
Created using vanilla javascript
KrouniHatim - Dec22
---

metadata.name: Influence no.1: Circular Expansion #98
metadata.description:
"Circular Expansion" is an abstract artwork focusing on the composition and connection of elements.
This is the first artwork from the "Influence" series. Similar to my emphasis on the importance of connections between small elements and larger elements in previous artworks, this series tries to show the connection and influence of elements on each other in a different and newer way by combining different algorithms and using multiple color palettes.
Various sizes and densities and 12 color palettes have been used.

metadata.name: Bone Work (Gulf of Mexico) 2022 #104
metadata.description:
Bone Work (Gulf of Mexico) 2022 centres on sixteen fragments of dead coral found by the artist on the shores of the Yucatán Peninsula on the Gulf Of Mexico. Collected and 3D scanned the titular ‘bones’ in the work consist of corals which have perished from exposure to ocean heating from climate change, agricultural nitrogen runoff from the American midwest or local pollution, or a combination of all three.

Floating above a virtual representation of the Gulf the bones are re-positioned in each edition using fxhash to generate different outputs. The public can rearrange the bones by clicking and dragging upon them on a desktop or hand held device. Dragging in the background allows one to look around the floating sculpture. On reload the new arrangement is lost and the original configuration returns. The work slowly turns in space however this can be switched off using the R command on a desktop device.

The work operates on local Yucatán time (GMT-5) and is an annual solar simulation. The sun rises on the world of the work simultaneously as in Mexico and sets accordingly to show dusk and night. Thus the work can look radically different from each hour to the next across the year. One will witness long days in the summer and short in winter - accurate across the solar year.

Bone Work (Gulf of Mexico) 2022 extends John Gerrard's twenty year engagement with simulation as a contemporary art form and further develops ecological themes as seen in Dust Storm (Dalhart, Texas) 2008, Western Flag (Spindletop, Texas) 2017 + more recently Flare (Oceania) 2022 - seen at the artist debut at Pace Gallery, New York in Summer 2022 and originally premiered by Art of Change 21 at the UN Climate Change Conference / COP26 Glasgow at the University of Glasgow / Hunterian Gallery.

Bone Work (Gulf of Mexico) 2022 is John Gerrard’s first work on the Tezos blockchain and his first project on fxhash.

20% of proceeds from this project are dedicated equally to support The Herbert Franke Archive at ZKM via https://www.tribute-hwf.com and to regenerate.farm, the artists fund to support creative regenerative agricultural projects globally.

Bone Work (Gulf of Mexico) 2022
Edition of 365 Unique Generative Worlds
(If not sold out one work to be burnt each day until the edition is closed out. Works are typically burnt once a week by the artist on a Monday x 7 works)

Credits
Producer : Werner Poetzelberger
Programmer : Helmut Bressler
Engine : WebGL

metadata.name: Vers #227
metadata.description:
Vers

A flexibility in regards to position.

V : Switch the top to the bottom or vice versa
A : Toggle reveal animation/title card
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

4’33’” - a 3-movement composition by experimental composer John Cage. 

4’33” - THE MUSIC.  Cage wrote the score instructing performers not to play their instruments during the entire duration of the piece. Though it is often perceived as silence, it is in that context: the sounds of the environment, being that, it becomes music.  

4’33” - fx(hash) gentk, you get a flatpack stained glass tea hut. Your tea hut, prefabbed with fixed geometry and fixed color palette straight out of the box. 

The code interprets your hash as pertaining to where and how you build this hut. Though it might look like noise or glitch, it is in the context: the light in us colors the shadows, reflections, celebrations of life, and acts in life.  

If you listen c a . r .    e .    f .      u .     l .        l.        y you can hear the reverberation, sounds of splendid joy in it. 

p5.js may take about 4.33 seconds to draw. Press 1 to save png.
